1. Classification using k-nearest neighbors

We start exploring the world of data modeling by using the K-Nearest Neightbors (k-NN) algorithm. The k-NN algorithm is one of the classic supervised machine learning algorithms which assumes that similar points are close to each other.

In our case, we'll use the k-NN algorithm to predict the presence of cardiovascular disease (CVD) using all the other variables as features in the given data set. I.e. the target variable that we are interested in is cardio.

We have the data so now, let's put it to use.

To teach the k-NN algorithm (or any other machine learning algorithm) to recognize patterns, we need training data. However, to assess how well a model has learned these patterns, we require test data which is new and unseen by the trained model. It's important to note that the test set is not revealed to the model until after the training is complete.

So, to estimate the performance of a model, we may use a basic train-test split. The term "split" is there because we literally split the data into two sets.

### Code - Standardization

# Importing the standardization function 'scale'
from sklearn.preprocessing import scale

# Creating a list of the names of the numerical features in the given dataframe
numerical_features = ["age", "height", "weight", "ap_hi", "ap_lo"]

# standardizing the numerical features in x_train data
x_train[numerical_features] = scale(x_train[numerical_features])

# standardizing the numerical features in x_test data
x_test[numerical_features] = scale(x_test[numerical_features])

In K-NN models, the similarity between data points is measured based on the distance metric. The distance calculation will be dominated by the features with the larger scale in the case that the features are on different scales. This is why standadization is important, since it ensures that all features contribute equally to the distance calculation. Without standardization, the algorithm will identify the k-nearest neighbors based on the unstandardized features, meaning that it will compute distances using the original scale of the features. As a result, The neighbors may be biased toward features with larger scales, such as height in our case.

a) In our case positive class represents the presence of the cardiovascular disease, while the negative class represents the absence of the cardiovascular disease. The top left cell in the matrix represents the correctly predicted instances of the negative class (True Negative). The top right cell represents the incorrectly predicted instances as positive when they were negative (False Positive). The bottom left represents the incorrectly predicted instances as negative when they were positive (False Negative). Finally, the bottom right represents the correctly predicted instances of the positive class (True Positive). b) Based on the confusion matrix, it can be said that the model performs better with the negative class in which we do not have a case of cardiovascular disease. The differences could arise of the fact that we have '0' cases more than the '1' cases, which allows model to learn about the patterns that lead to '0' case. The accuracy is the ratio of correctly predicted instances to the total instances, which is 0.723, which can be considered as 'decent', but it is encouraged to improve this value. The precision value answers the question of 'when it predicts yes, how often is it?', and the value for this is 0.512, which is totally unsatisfactory. Recall attempts to find an answer for the question of 'What proportion of actual positives was identified correctly?', and the result for it 0.482, which is again very low value. c) In our dataset, there are more healthy patients than the one with the cardiovascular disease, which leads to class imbalance in our dataset. The accuracy can be misleading metric in the datasets with class imbalance.

You randomly divided the data into two sets, one for training the k-NN model and the other for evaluating its performance. However, randomness is not the thing we really need, and in fact, it's not something we even desire. Instead, what we do want is to keep track of each step we're making and exporing. This said, the reproducibility of the results is extremely important in research. To achieve this, we can utilize a random seed, with which we can re-run the codes and get the exact same results than before.

For example, we can use a fixed seed when we're shuffling the data before splitting it into training and test sets. This ensures that when we're re-runing the code, we obtain exactly the same partitions of the data in each split.

One really common evaluation metric is the area under the receiver operating characteristic (AUROC, AUC or AUC-ROC). It provides a measure of a model's ability to distinguish between classes, especially in binary classification tasks between the positive class and the negative class. (There sure are multiclass and multilabel cases too, but they are out of scope here.)

In our case, individuals who have a CVD form the positive class. As the name of the measure suggests, it combines two keys aspects to interpret a model's performance: ROC curves are about the trade-off between the true positive rate and the false positive rate, the former representing the model's ability to correctly identify individuals with a CVD (true positives) and the latter measuring the model's tendency to incorrectly classify individuals without a CVD as if they have the disease (false positives). Thus, the area beneath the curve is simply the AUROC, a single numerical value, that summarizes the overall performance.

2. Classification accuracy using leave-one-out cross-validation

While the train-test split may provide us with an unbiased estimate of the performance, we only evaluate the model once. Especially when dealing with small datasets, a test set itself will be very small. How can we be sure that the evaluation is accurate with this small test set and not just a good (or bad) luck? And what if we'd like to compare two models and the other seems to be better -- how can we be sure that it's not just a coincidence?

Well, there's a great help available and it's called cross-validation. With its help, we can split the dataset into multiple different training and test sets, which allows us to evaluate models across various data partitions. This time, we'll take a closer look at the leave-one-out cross-validation.

### Code - Leave-one-out cross-validation

from numpy import mean
from numpy import absolute

# collecting the features as an array named features
features = cardio_sample.drop(columns=['cardio'])

# collecting the target variable as an array named labels
labels = cardio_sample['cardio']

# Creating a list of the names of the numerical features in the given dataframe
numerical_features = ["age", "height", "weight", "ap_hi", "ap_lo"]

# standardizing the numerical features in features data
features[numerical_features] = scale(features[numerical_features])

# Building our model
knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)


# Defining cross-validation method to use
cv = LeaveOneOut()

# using LOOCV to evaluate the model
scores = cross_val_score(knn_model, features, labels, scoring = 'accuracy', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)

print(mean(absolute(scores)))

0.722

3. Model selection with leave-one-out cross-validation

So far, we've trained one model at a time and I've given the value of k for you. Accuracy is what it is (no spoilers here), but could we still do a little better? Let's explore that possibility through a process known as hyperparameter tuning. The cross-validation is especially important tool for this task. Note here, that model selection and model evaluation (or assessment) are two different things: We use model selection to estimate the performance of various models to identify the model which is most likely to provide the "best" predictive performance for the task. And when we have found this most suitable model, we assess its perfomance and generalisation power on unseen data.

This time, we're going to train multiple models, let's say 30, and our goal is to select the best K-Nearest Neighbors model from this set. Most models come with various hyperparameters that require careful selection, and the k-NN model is no exception. Although we're talking about the number of neighbors here, it's important to note that k-NN also has several other hyperparameters. However, for the sake of simplicity, this time we'll focus solely on fine-tuning the number of nearest neighbors, that is, the value of k.

Let's focus on the model selection part here for the sake of comprehending the cross-validation itself. We'll get later on the whole pipeline, which also includes model assessment.

### Code - Select best model

# Creating a list of k values from 1 to 30
k_values = [i for i in range (1,31)]

# Creating an empty list to store the scores
scores = []

# Creating a KNeighborsClassifier object with every value in k_values with a loop
# And calculating the accuracy of each model and appending it to the scores list
for k in k_values:
    cv = LeaveOneOut()
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    score = cross_val_score(knn, features, labels, cv=cv)
    scores.append(np.mean(score))

# Printing the maximum accuracy value
print('The maximum accuracy value is', max(scores))

The maximum accuracy value is 0.758

In the case of bigger K values, the decision boundary is less sensitive to individual data points, the model could oversimplify the data. Also, if the data has class imbalance, the model will be biased. In our case, the model with high K values will favor the healthy patients than the healthy patients with cardiovascular disease, as the first class dominates the other one.

### Code - Train with whole data

#create a range of k values
k_values = [i for i in range (1,31)]

#create a list to store the accuracies for the new models
new_accuracies = []

#train and evaluate 30 k-NN models using the whole dataset
for k in k_values:

    #train a k-NN model for each k value
    knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k)

    #train the model on the whole dataset
    knn_model.fit(features, labels)

    #make predictions on the whole dataset
    y_pred = knn_model.predict(features)

    #calculate the accuracy for the current k
    accuracy = accuracy_score(labels, y_pred)

    #add the accuracy for the current k to the list of the accuracies for all the models
    new_accuracies.append(accuracy)

The optimal value for the k is 1, now, and it has around 100% accuracy. This result is due to the fact that we used the entired dataset for both test and training data, which led us to the overfitting. When the k was 1, the model assigned the label of each data to the label of its nearest neighbor, which was the exact same point. In training data, the model just memorized the label of each data in the case of k=1, therefore it achieved 100% accuracy in the test data which was entirely identical to the training data. The reliability of this model is really low, since it can only achieve this accuracy in this test set which is identical to the training set. If a new and totally different test set is introduced, it is highly likely that the model will make incorrect predictions. b) The same dataset should not be used for the test and training set, because the model will likely to be overfitted and biased, and make very poor predictions on the data which is different from the training data.

5. Comparison of ridge regression and k-NN regression

The previous exercises were about classification. Now, we are ready to see another kind of supervised learning - regression - as we are changing our main goal from predicting discrete classes (healty/sick) to estimating continuous values. The following exercises are going to involve utilizing two different regression models, Ridge Regression and K-Nearest Neighbors (k-NN) Regression, and our goal is to evaluate and compare the performances of these two models.

Let's change the dataset to make the following exercises more intuitive. The new dataset is about brushtail possums and it includes variables such as

  • sex: Gender, either male (0) or female (1)
  • age: Age in years
  • len_head: Head length in cm
  • width_skull: Skull width in mm
  • len_total: Total length in cm
  • len_tail: Tail length in cm
  • len_foot: Foot length
  • len_earconch: Ear conch length

Regression allows us to examine relationships between two or more variables. This relationship is represented by an equation, which itself represents how a change in one variable affects another on average. For example, we could examine how a change in possum's total length affects, on average, its estimated age.

Regarding the k-NN, we have already get familiar with the optimization of the k value. The idea behind the k-NN is the same as previously in classification, the output isn't a class anymore but a continuous value. So, for now, we can stick to the optimal k value. However, for Ridge Regression, we'll focus on the hyperparameter called $\lambda$ (read as 'lambda'), the regularization term (or penalty term or L2 penalty, how ever we'd like to call it), and try to find its optimal value for this task. After the model selection for both regression is performed, we compare the chosen models using a metric called mean absolute error (MAE).

In [19]:
### Code - CV for Ridge regression and k-NN regression
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

# Seting the range of the lambda hyperparameters
range_of_lambda = 2.0 ** np.arange(-10, 11)

# An empty set to collect MAE values for the performed ridge regression
mae_values_for_ridge = []

# Performing ridge regression models with different lambda hyperparameters and collecting the MAE values

for alpha in range_of_lambda:
    ridge_model = Ridge(alpha = alpha)
    cv=LeaveOneOut()
    y_pred = cross_val_predict(ridge_model, x_train, y_train, cv = cv)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred)
    mae_values_for_ridge.append(mae)

# Identifying the optimal lambda for ridge regression
optimal_lambda = range_of_lambda[np.argmin(mae_values_for_ridge)]

# Displaying the lambda values versus resultant MAEs
plt.figure()
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(np.log2(range_of_lambda), mae_values_for_ridge,color = 'blue', marker = 'o')
plt.title('Ridge Regression')
plt.xlabel('log2(Lambda)')
plt.ylabel('MAE')

# Displaying a vertical line for the optimal lambda
plt.axvline(np.log2(optimal_lambda), color = 'red', linestyle = ':', label = f'Optimal lambda is {optimal_lambda:.2e}')

# Showing legend
plt.legend()


# Setting the range of k (number of neighbors)
range_of_k = np.arange(1, 31)

# An empty set to collect MAE values for the performed k-nn
mae_values_for_knn = []

# Performing KNN models with different k's and collecting the MAE values
for k in range_of_k:
    knn_model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors = k)
    cv=LeaveOneOut()
    y_pred = cross_val_predict(knn_model, x_train, y_train, cv = cv)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred)
    mae_values_for_knn.append(mae)

# Find the optimal k for k-NN Regression
optimal_k = range_of_k[np.argmin(mae_values_for_knn)]

# Displaying a vertical line for the optimal k
plt.figure()
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(range_of_k, mae_values_for_knn,color = 'blue', marker = 'o')
plt.title('K-NN regression')
plt.xlabel('Number of Neighbors')
plt.ylabel('MAE')

# Displaying a vertical line for the optimal k
plt.axvline(optimal_k, color = 'red', linestyle = ':', label = f'Optimal k is {optimal_k:.2e}')

# Displaying Legend
plt.legend()
Out[19]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x26235792c90>

a) The Lambda that gives the lowest MAE is 512, while the optimal K is 16. b) The mean of absolute differences between the predicted and actual values is called MAE. In our case, the target variable is age. Thus, MAE represents the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual ages in years. If the MAE is 3, it means that there is an average 3 years difference between our predictions and actual age values.

The cross-validation was employed for model selection and at this point, we have the optimal hyperparameter settings for each model. Let's finally assess both models using the test set. ## Code - Evaluating the selected models

# Building the model with optimal lambda
ridge_model = Ridge(alpha = optimal_lambda)

# Fiting the ridge regression model using the whole training set
ridge_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Performing predictions on the test set
y_pred_ridge = ridge_model.predict(x_test)

# Printing the mean absolute error
print('MAE for Ridge Regression is', mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_ridge))

# Building the model with optimal k
knn_model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors = optimal_k)

# Fitting k-nn model using the whole training set
knn_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Performing predictions on the test set
y_pred_knn = knn_model.predict(x_test)

# Printing the mean absolute error
print('MAE for K-NN Regression is',mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_knn))

a) The MAE for both models are decent, thus it could be said that both of models performed in a satisfactory degree. The comparison of the MAE values of these models reveal the fact that the Ridge Model performs slightly better than the K-NN model in terms of predicting the age values. b) The MAEs done with cross-validation helps us to identify the optimal hyperparameters, however MEAs based on the test data provided more realistic outcomes. The models built with cross-validation could be overfitted and potentially perform really poor on unseen data.
